As a systems automator, I need the ability to set specific JIRA parameters from the command line. This reduces build & experiment harness complexity by obviating the need to edit bundled script with JIRA standalone.

For example, heap sizes; which are hard coded in {{setenv.sh}} for the standalone Tomcat.

Using Bash Parameter Expansion, these values can be pulled from the parent shell environment or use a default if not specified. From the {{bash}} manual page:
{quote}
$\{parameter:-word}
              Use Default Values.  If parameter is unset or null, the expansion of word is substituted.  Otherwise, the value of parameter is substituted.
{quote}

E.g.:
{noformat}
pdzwart@Mjolnir:~[14:33:14](0,0)$ ./setenv.sh 
BAR
pdzwart@Mjolnir:~[14:33:16](0,0)$ FOO=gnarf ./setenv.sh 
gnarf
pdzwart@Mjolnir:~[14:33:21](0,0)$ cat setenv.sh 
FOO=${FOO:-BAR}

echo $FOO
pdzwart@Mjolnir:~[14:33:26](0,0)$
{noformat}

In the context of {{setenv.sh}} (and other script configuration files and variables, like {{user.sh}}, {{JIRA_USER}}), as an example; the {{JVM_MINIMUM_MEMORY}} environment variable assignment can be changed from:
{noformat}
JVM_MINIMUM_MEMORY="384m"
{noformat}
To:
{noformat}
JVM_MINIMUM_MEMORY =${JVM_MINIMUM_MEMORY:-"384m"}
{noformat}

Which would allow the setting of this value from the shell environment with exported variables.

Strongly suggest using this mechanism of parameter expansion with the following list of variables:
* {{JVM_MINIMUM_MEMORY}}
* {{JVM_MAXIMUM_MEMORY}}
* {{JVM_EXTRA_ARGS}}

